South Africa Stocks: Anglo American, BHP Billiton, Metorex

-- B y   R o b e r t   B r a n d
-- 
2011-04-08T16:05:37Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-08/south-africa-stocks-anglo-american-bhp-billiton-metorex.html
South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE  Africa  All
Share Index rose 173.02, or 0.5 percent, to 32,806.27, at the 5
p.m. close in Johannesburg, bringing its weekly gain to 2.5
percent.  The following stocks were among the most active stocks in
the South African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AGL)  , the diversified mining company
that makes up 11 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, gained 9.85 rand, or 2.8 percent, to 362.85 rand. Copper
rallied for a fourth day and zinc climbed on optimism global
economic growth will sustain demand for industrial metals. Lead
advanced to the highest level in three years and aluminum
reached the highest price since April 2008.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s largest mining
company, climbed 5.60 rand, or 2 percent, to 280.70 rand, the
highest closing price since Feb. 17.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (ANG)  , Africa’s largest gold
producer, gained 4.90 rand, or 1.5 percent, to 337 rand after
the metal rose 1.1 percent to a record.  Metorex Ltd. (MTX)  , a copper producer, dropped 5 cents,
or 0.7 percent, to 7.05 rand after reaching its highest level
since October 2008 earlier. Vale SA, the world’s second-biggest
miner, offered to buy Metorex for 7.4 billion rand ($1.1
billion), or 7.35 rand a share.  SacOil Holdings Ltd. (SCL SJ), an oil and natural gas
exploration company, snapped two days of gains, losing 6 cents,
or 2.9 percent, to 1.99 rand. The company said it has started
trading its shares on the Alternative Investment Market of the
London Stock Exchange.  Vivendi Income Fund Ltd. (VIF SJ), a commercial, retail and
industrial property investor, rallied the most since it listed
in November, gaining 29 cents, or 6.1 percent, to 5.01 rand.
Vivendi said it will distribute a maiden payment of 9.96 cents
per linked unit to shareholders for the first half through
February.  To contact the reporter on this story:
